				<img src="image.php?s=806f2e17e5b773de385d7e932a795e2b&amp;u=29741&amp;dateline=1459520709" alt="MI Redeux's Avatar" title="MI Redeux's Avatar" />
			</a>
			 
			
				<hr />
				<dl class="userinfo_extra">
					<dt>Join Date</dt> <dd>Aug 2012</dd>
					
					
					<dt>Posts</dt> <dd>5,892</dd>	
					
				</dl>
				
				
				<div class="imlinks">
					    
				</div>
			
		</div>
		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Stigma Around Bittorrent
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1808948">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Bittorrent is sometimes used by more legitimate corporations/organizations for distribution than it has been in the past, but I still find situations where using torrents as the preferred distribution method makes a lot of sense is not used, despite creating torrents and using torrents being extremely trivial in both cases nowadays and available on all platforms for some reasons, presumably because it is tainted by ignorance propagated by RIAA/MPAA and the ilk. It's extremely prevalent for Linux distributions as an example, but Freebsd does not provide an official torrent source for some reason for their releases, instead still wasting resources on FTP distributions as the primary method, despite that being really slow for end users. I've seeded terabytes worth of just Debian 7.4 stable isos as an example, and would have thrown up torrents for official isos with OpenBSD and FreeBSD as well on one of my servers, but they do not bother with such (OpenBSD rationalizes this as encouraging purchase of the discs as donations, which is whatever IMO). So, that is kind of a retarded waste of money nowadays. Bittorrent's one of the most revolutionary technologies of our life times and Bram Cohen is a hero genius* IMO, so it is unfortunate to see Bittorrent continued to be maligned instead of exploited as much as possible.<br />
<br />
* Cohen's one of the few people alive who are just on a different plane from the rest of the planet in their understanding of the universe, so I hate seeing him grouped with nefarious social groups instead of more generally celebrated. I do wonder what all he would have accomplished had he stayed dedicated to mathematics instead though. Bittorrent's a rare example of how extremely beneficial to technology development that open software/free software can be though as a number of really great extensions to the original protocol were made by outsiders and those have propagated to the entire ecosystem well. Generally though great execution of ideas seems to occur with developing the idea behind closed doors, which is counter intuitive to me and is against the meme that is often parroted.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
